1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:05,000
Gemma HerbalCare is built for places where professional care may be far away, expensive, or delayed.

2
00:00:05,000 --> 00:00:18,000
This is not a free-form herbal chatbot. It is a safety-first navigator: red flags are checked before any local plant is shown.

3
00:00:18,000 --> 00:00:30,000
The app is local-first and Gemma-ready, so the same workflow can run with a local model such as Gemma through Ollama for private, low-connectivity settings.

4
00:00:30,000 --> 00:00:45,000
The herb library keeps curated records: plant names, reference images, safety warnings, evidence level, interactions, and local availability.

5
00:00:45,000 --> 00:00:55,000
This matters because the safest plant advice starts with correct identification and clear limits, not guessing.

6
00:00:55,000 --> 00:01:08,000
The safety page draws the product boundary. The assistant is educational only, not a doctor, not a diagnosis, and not a prescription.

7
00:01:08,000 --> 00:01:20,000
For severe symptoms, suspected malaria, breathing trouble, pregnancy bleeding, cancer cure claims, or chest pain, the system suppresses herbal substitution.

8
00:01:20,000 --> 00:01:35,000
The consultation form collects context first: location, symptoms, age, duration, pregnancy status, care access, medicines, conditions, and allergies.

9
00:01:35,000 --> 00:01:48,000
Care access changes the answer. If a clinic or community health worker is reachable, herbs are framed as reference only.

10
00:01:48,000 --> 00:02:00,000
If care is not reachable right now, the app gives temporary harm-reduction guidance, but keeps warning that proven care is still the safest path.

11
00:02:00,000 --> 00:02:14,000
Accessibility is part of the design. Camera and microphone support are marked as phase 2, for local OCR, voice input, and visual triage support.

12
00:02:14,000 --> 00:02:24,000
The read-aloud button works now with browser text-to-speech, helping users who cannot read, cannot type, have poor vision, or are older adults.

13
00:02:24,000 --> 00:02:39,000
Case one: child diarrhea after unsafe water. The lifesaving step is ORS and safe water. Herbs are supportive only, never the main treatment.

14
00:02:39,000 --> 00:02:52,000
Case two: long-term food source planning. The app can suggest simple resilience steps such as sweet potato vines, familiar leafy foods, and chickens only when water, shade, and protection are realistic.

15
00:02:52,000 --> 00:03:00,000
Case three: fever and suspected malaria. The app pushes rapid testing and proven antimalarial care. It does not recommend raw bark or herbs as a substitute.
